<section id="chapter1">
  <h2>1. Structuring Documents</h2>

  <p>
    Chapter 1 focuses on those parts of your websites that recur and are similar or identical on every page. You will learn how to set up the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> and create a base structure in the <code>&lt;body&gt;</code>.
  </p>

  <h3>Recipes</h3>

  <ol>
    <li>Define the natural language</li>
    <li>Describe the document</li>
    <li>Set the viewport width</li>
    <li>Optimize rendering order</li>
    <li>Structure the document</li>
  </ol>
</section>

<section id="chapter2">
  <h2>2. Structuring Pages</h2>

  <p>In Chapter 2, you leave the base structure of your website and move into the page itself. The foundation of a well-designed page is grouping elements, landmarks, and headings. You learn how to use &lt;section&gt;, &lt;nav&gt;, or &lt;article&gt; efficiently and how to combine them with headings to create a sound document outline.</p>
  
  <h3>Recipes</h3>

  <ol>
    <li>Create navigation landmarks</li>
    <li>Create form landmarks</li>
    <li>Label landmarks</li>
    <li>Structure the main content</li>
    <li>Create a sound document outline</li>
    <li>Present content in order</li>
  </ol>
</section>

<section id="chapter3">
  <h2>3. Linking Content</h3>
  
  <p>Hyperlinks are the basis of the World Wide Web. That is why Chapter 3, which is all about linking content, is one of the book’s most extensive chapters. It analyzes the characteristics of the &lt;a&gt; element and helps you apply it efficiently. You’ll learn how to link different types of content, images, and groups of elements. One recipe focuses on client-side routing and what to consider when linking pages in a single application. Another addresses how to visually style links.</p>

  <h3>Recipes</h3>

  <ol>
    <li>Pick the right element</li>
    <li>Style links</li>
    <li>Create download links</li>
    <li>Create email links</li>
    <li>Link images</li>
    <li>Inform users of changing context</li>
    <li>Fix client-side rendering</li>
    <li>Add links to groups of elements</li>
  </ol>
</section>

<section id="chapter4">
  <h2>4. Performing Actions</h2>

  <p>Chapter 4 is similar to the previous chapter, except that it puts the &lt;button&gt; element in the spotlight. You’ll learn different techniques for labeling buttons and how to use them with the most common ARIA attributes.</p>
  
